On Wed, 21 Feb 2001, Bob Krygowski wrote:

&gt; Does anyone know if you can step through your code while running JUnit
&gt; tests?  I have been using JBuilder 4 and have only successfully been able to
&gt; hit break points in the main method (which just ends up taking you to
&gt; underlying JUnit code).  In debugging I would like to be able to step
&gt; through the individual tests and step into the actual class that is being
&gt; tested to see what is going on.
&gt; 
&gt; Any thoughts?

I do this all the time.  The trick is to ensure your tests are thread 
safe.  Typically when I have trouble with something in the debugger,
it&#39;s because I&#39;ve molested a visible swing component from my main test
thread instead of the swing event thread.

I&#39;ve collected a number of methods to make this easier.

On my AllTests.java file I have:

  /**
   * Safely call doClick() on the specified JButton.
   * @param button The button to doClick().
   */
  public static void safeDoClick(final JButton button) {
    try {
      SwingUtilities.invokeAndWait(
        new Runnable() {
          /**
           *  Main processing method for the AllTests object
           */
          public void run() {
            button.doClick();
          }
        }
      );
    }
    catch (Exception ex) {
      ex.printStackTrace();
    }
  }

I use this within tests like so:

//    foo.setWatched( buttonOne ); // not thread safe, dummy!
    AllTests.safeDoClick( buttonOne );

